pr_review_comment_body:
@amanwriter just so that we are on the same page. The purpose of trace_id is that it is initially assigned the first time a request comes into a _vyked service cloud_ and the same one is used for all calls that occur between services in order to fulfil the original request so that we can trace what happened for any specific request.

The way I was originally thinking about it the trace_id only needs to be checked when a request is received and if it isn't there it just gets added when the response is sent. This can happen purely at the packet level and hence all of this should not be necessary.

PS: Also should be done for pub subs also.

There are a few stages called "Cooking" finished:

```
        if (state.equals("10") || state.equals("11") || state.equals("12")) {
            setStage(Constants.COOK_STATUS_FINISH);
```

this is to follow the interface of TensorFlow. https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/while_loop
Using class does make API more well defined, but it requires users to write more code to define it. I don't know what is the best way. 
@piiswrong what's your opinion?

Example that creates a root span for all handlers (and attaches a ``Context`` in the handler request):
```python
from ddtrace.contrib.tornado.middlewares import TraceMiddleware

class MainHandler(tornado.web.RequestHandler):
    @tornado.gen.coroutine
    def get(self):
        pass

def make_app():
    return tornado.web.Application([
        (r"/", MainHandler),
    ])

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = make_app()
    http_server = app.listen(8000)
    TraceMiddleware(http_server, tracer, service='mytornado')
    tornado.ioloop.IOLoop.current().start()
```

Here's the full definition of the struct from Windows SDK v7.0's shellapi.h:

```
 typedef struct _NOTIFYICONDATAA {
    DWORD cbSize;
    HWND hWnd;
    UINT uID;
    UINT uFlags;
    UINT uCallbackMessage;
    HICON hIcon;
#if (NTDDI_VERSION < NTDDI_WIN2K)
    CHAR   szTip[64];
#endif
#if (NTDDI_VERSION >= NTDDI_WIN2K)
    CHAR   szTip[128];
    DWORD dwState;
    DWORD dwStateMask;
    CHAR   szInfo[256];
    union {
        UINT  uTimeout;
        UINT  uVersion;  // used with NIM_SETVERSION, values 0, 3 and 4
    } DUMMYUNIONNAME;
    CHAR   szInfoTitle[64];
    DWORD dwInfoFlags;
#endif
#if (NTDDI_VERSION >= NTDDI_WINXP)
    GUID guidItem;
#endif
#if (NTDDI_VERSION >= NTDDI_VISTA)
    HICON hBalloonIcon;
#endif
} NOTIFYICONDATAA, *PNOTIFYICONDATAA;
```

@hwwhww `@property` methods don't actually provide any protection from mutation *unless* you create a `setter` which throws.  I'd be good with doing that but it should probably be done with our own decorator that automatically creates the `setter` function.  Something like a new decorator:

```python
@immutable_property
def something(self):
    ...
```

Would it make sense consolidate [error reporting](https://github.com/Azure/azure-cli/blob/functionapp/src/command_modules/azure-cli-appservice/azure/cli/command_modules/appservice/custom.py#L1019-L1026)  to code like:
```python
    for e in ['blob', 'queue', 'table']:
        if not getattr(endpoints, e, None):
              error_message = "Storage account has no '{}' endpoint. It must have table, queue, and blob endpoints all enabled".format(e)
```

@vvb - `auto_refresh` should also be an attribute of `UcsSession`. 
`self.__auto_refresh = auto_refresh`.
This will help us in saving auto_refresh parameter, which will help us when serializing the handle.

Tag is named `'laststatus'` (with single quotes), there is no `laststatus` tag: it works only because Vim also does substring matching. Code should be enclosed in *two* backticks, not one. Line too long, wrap at 80’th column.

Also many other notes are aligned with `n` in `note`, though not all AFAIK, can’t say what is more common. I align with `n` when I remember to align with `n`.

// And information is already in troubleshooting, third Vim issue.

Return type can probably be:

```
@return {Observable<Action>}
```

@chshu Isn't otPlatTimeGet() equal to otPlatAlarmMicroGetNow() ? It seems this effectively does:

```
receivedFrame->mIeInfo->mTimestamp = (int32_t)nrf_802154_first_symbol_timestamp_get(time, p_data[0]);
```

I think it might be helpful to put the simple implementation first.  Unlike most cases, this one isn't about a workaround of the simple version for PyPy but rather an optimization for CPython.

Either way, I think it strongly needs a comment along the lines of:
```C++
// Alternate approach for CPython: this does the same as the above, but optimized
// using the CPython API so as to avoid an unneeded attribute lookup.
```

@stephanie-wang yes, bullets 1-3 are exactly what I have in mind.

For singleton chain case (default deployment), both `ActAsTail()` and `ActAsHead()` will be true.  So if node func does not error, the tail func _will_ be run, and hence we will exactly get 1 reply.

For distributed, >1-chain case, the `ChainReplicate()` interface specifically designed for ray's redis module lacks this distributed support (i.e., propagating the update).  (credis' native `MemberPut_RedisCommand()/Put()` do handle propagation, of course.) . Since it's not handled right now we should make sure 1-node case is correct at the moment.
